caption:
It has been a most incredible 16 months. This is the B-Society 23-24 executive team signing off for the last time. 

To the general engineering student body, it was a privilege and an honor to serve the B-Society undergraduate engineering student body throughout these last 16 months. Please continue to engage with the society as it is taken to new heights.

To the previous executive teams that have come before us, thank you for being the giants whose shoulders we stood on. Thank you for the work you put into the society, and the strong foundations that we were able to build upon. 

And finally to the incoming executive team, we wish you nothing but the best. It has been a pleasure to work with all of you in your previous capacities, and we are sure that your passion, enthusiasm, and hard work will carry you far in your new positions.

- Dylan, Jake, Grace, Michael, and Thomas

caption:
Here are our award winners for S24!

Engineering Society Leadership Excellence Award
Awarded to someone who displays leadership within the Faculty, University and/or community at-large. Congrats to Amir!

Igor Ivkovic Teaching Excellence Award
Awarded to a member of the teaching team within the University of Waterloo Engineering Faculty rewarding teaching excellence. The Award, previously called the “Teaching Excellence Award”, was renamed after Igor Ivkovic, a Systems Design Engineering Professor, who exemplified the spirit of the Award. He dedicated his life to his students, colleagues, and the University of Waterloo community. He advanced teaching in Engineering through his care and enthusiasm. The Award was renamed to honour his legacy and to promote his dedication to our community. The students, faculty and Waterloo community will always remember how much Professor Igor cared. Congratulations to Reem Roufail!

Friend of Natalie Award
Awarded to a Faculty and Staff Member who have gone out of their way to support the mental health of students. Congrats to Pendar Mahmoudi!

Paul Harlick Award
Awarded to the most engaged and enthusiastic class reps! Congrats Jordan and Garvit EE '28. 

President's Awards
Awarded by each of B-Soc Exec to commissioners/directors who have given their all to improve our society! Congrats to Muhammad, Sumnit, Lino, Celia, and Kate

caption:
Launched in 2016, Engineering Day’s mission is simple: to give students a few hours off from classes to have some fun in the sun. Working with the Waterloo Engineering Society (@uwengsoc), the official student council representing the student body, the Faculty organizes the event in July each year. Hundreds of students flock to line up for burgers, paint themselves purple and drop professors in the ‘dunk tank.’   

Engineering Day and other traditions within the faculty are critical in creating community and forging friendships and memories that will last a lifetime. These traditions are explored in more depth in the #UWaterlooMagazine. To read the full story visit the link in out bio.

#UWaterloo 🖤💛💜

The Engineering Society is currently looking to form its team of Commissioners for the Fall 2024 Academic term!

We employ Commissioners to assist the executive with the Society's day-to-day operations and explore potential avenues for growth in the Society. Commissioners work closely with Directors and Executives to ensure that all the Society's services and events run successfully. These positions will be for seven months, from June 2024 to December 2024.

We require commissioners to be undergraduate Waterloo Engineering Students. Both on and off term students are encouraged to apply, but preference will be given those on-term in the fall students.

Application can be found here: https://bit.ly/F24CommApplications. Link in bio!

Deadline to Apply: Sunday, May 26th at 11:59pm

caption:
Meet the judges and our mentors for tomorrow’s FRAME Designathon! 🤩

caption:
UX and product design… what’s the difference? 🤔

You might have heard these roles being used interchangeably, and they are quite similar—but each have different overall focus in their job! Swipe and read to learn more 👀

***

On one hand, UX design is…
👉 focused on creating beautiful interfaces and building seamless interaction, and ensure the whole user experience is enjoyable
⭐️ is a more specialized role as they have a more specific, design-oriented focus in their responsibilities
🧰 experience can be involved with interaction design, visual design, UX research, and other similar roles

On the other hand, product design…
🔎 is involved with the entire product creation process, with a more business-oriented focus as they are responsible for discovering and defining a problem and creating a design solution
✨ sometimes associated with physical design, also known as industrial design
💭 experience can be involved in project and/or product management, UX design, and more!

***

#uwaterloo #ux #uxdesign #productdesign #designtips

caption:
🚨BIG ANNOUNCEMENT!!!🚨

We’re excited to announce that @uw_ux will be launching a new mentorship program! 🎉 Currently on the lookout for mentors and mentees… 👀

***

What is the mentorship program? 🤔
🔎 This is a 7 week long program pairs students with a mentor experienced with UX/UI, product, visual design, user research, and more!

🌱 Mentors will help their mentee(s) grow by sharing their knowledge and experiences, and providing guidance and advice. From resume/portfolio help, interview prep, case study reviews, goal setting, and so much more ✨🤩

👀 If you’re seeking to apply as a mentor, no prior mentorship experience required—just an open mind, solid foundation in design knowledge, and a desire to help a mentee grow! We’ll provide you with support and resources to grow ☺️

‼️MENTOR APPS DUE JUNE 18 @ 11:59 PM EST‼️

===

What’s the objective of the program?
🫂 UW/UX seeks to strengthen the network of design students in Waterloo and make connections that go beyond a single coffee chat. We hope to foster a culture that encourages creativity and personal + professional growth 🌟

📚 This program aims to raise the bar of craft in Waterloo by providing students with valuable, 1-on-1 mentorship from experienced upper-years and professionals in the field.

👉 Interested in becoming a mentor/mentee for the mentorship program? Check the links in our bio to apply 😎

***

caption:
Wesley Chun, one of the speakers at Hack with AI, talked about “Reflections on a career in Software Engineering” today.

📍 SPEAKER BIO
WESLEY CHUN, MSCS, is a Google Developer Expert (GDE) in Google Cloud (GCP) & Google Workspace (GWS), author of Prentice Hall’s bestselling “Core Python” (corepython.com) series, co-author of “Python Web Development with Django” (withdjango.com), and has written for Linux Journal & CNET. He runs CyberWeb (cyberwebconsulting.com) specializing in Google developer tools/platforms, Python & App Engine migrations (appenginemigrations.com), and technical training. Wesley was one of the original Yahoo!Mail engineers and spent a dozen plus years on various Google product teams, covering their APIs on-stage, producing sample apps, tutorials, and serverless migration & GWS developers video series. He holds degrees in Computer Science, Mathematics, and Music from the University of California, is a Fellow of the Python Software Foundation, and loves to meet developers worldwide at conferences, user group events, and universities. Follow he/him @wescpy & dev.to/wescpy.

Interested in building with AI and cutting-edge technologies? Join us at the Hack with AI hackathon hosted by the 🪿 GeeseHacks team @geesehacks and GDSC University of Waterloo! This event invites university students and tech enthusiasts to dive into the world of artificial intelligence, exploring innovative use cases and crafting AI-driven applications.

🗓 Date: May 19th, 2024 9:30am -3:30pm
📍 Location: University of Waterloo E7 building
👥 Who Can Join: Open to all students, regardless of your background or technical ability!

caption:
WAT.ai is recruiting for Director positions! 

WAT.ai is both the Undergraduate Body of the Waterloo A.I. Institute and a member of the Sedra Student Design Centre. Our goal is to establish an environment to grow the future of AI talent at Waterloo. We provide opportunities to engage in impactful AI projects in concentrated research groups, providing educational resources and innovative challenges. If you want to be a part of the future of AI, there is no better time than now. Join us! 

We are looking to recruit several non-technical leadership roles, including Education Director, Finance Director, Marketing Director, Partnerships Director, and Website Director. Interviews will be done throughout July, the deadline to apply is July 31st!

caption:
🌟 ML API Camp Recap 🌟

We had an amazing time hosting our ML API Camp both in person and online! 🚀

caption:
Wesley Chun, one of the speakers at Hack with AI, talked about “Reflections on a career in Software Engineering” today.

📍 SPEAKER BIO
WESLEY CHUN, MSCS, is a Google Developer Expert (GDE) in Google Cloud (GCP) & Google Workspace (GWS), author of Prentice Hall’s bestselling “Core Python” (corepython.com) series, co-author of “Python Web Development with Django” (withdjango.com), and has written for Linux Journal & CNET. He runs CyberWeb (cyberwebconsulting.com) specializing in Google developer tools/platforms, Python & App Engine migrations (appenginemigrations.com), and technical training. Wesley was one of the original Yahoo!Mail engineers and spent a dozen plus years on various Google product teams, covering their APIs on-stage, producing sample apps, tutorials, and serverless migration & GWS developers video series. He holds degrees in Computer Science, Mathematics, and Music from the University of California, is a Fellow of the Python Software Foundation, and loves to meet developers worldwide at conferences, user group events, and universities. Follow he/him @wescpy & dev.to/wescpy.

Interested in building with AI and cutting-edge technologies? Join us at the Hack with AI hackathon hosted by the 🪿 GeeseHacks team @geesehacks and GDSC University of Waterloo! This event invites university students and tech enthusiasts to dive into the world of artificial intelligence, exploring innovative use cases and crafting AI-driven applications.

🗓 Date: May 19th, 2024 9:30am -3:30pm
📍 Location: University of Waterloo E7 building
👥 Who Can Join: Open to all students, regardless of your background or technical ability!
Sign up: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfh-ei_1g4K63tuJCC5HSdPZ5T2oMrc_fX9cE1DoxKKMck2-w/viewform?usp=sf_link

At Hack with AI, you’ll get the chance to:
🎊 Work in a high-energy, collaborative environment
🎊 Receive guidance from industry experts and seasoned mentors
🎊 Develop solutions that tackle real-world problems across various sectors

Cheeses will operate as normal ($4 for walk-ins, no fee for members) but you need to BRING something to GET something for the potluck!

Bring a takeout container too if you can 😉

caption: It’s was incredible for our team to qualify and compete in FSGP for the first time in 5 years! It was a long journey for us 2.5 years ago when we started this project from nothing and we couldn’t have been more proud of everyone that helped us build this solar car! Although we were not able to qualify for ASC, we’re still happy with what we were able to achieve over the duration of Scrutineering and FSGP with 100km on the track and a fastest lap of 5:55. We learned a lot during competition and from talking to other teams so we’ll be back with many ideas and improvements for our next car, MSXVI! As we look towards MSXVI, we’re looking for eager new members to help us in this new chapter of the team. Looking forward to seeing everyone in the Fall Term for recruitment!!
